      "text": "Change to systems of human activity is a critical dimension of computerization. Bodker and Christiansen, Robinson, and Axel mention that designing socially embedded computer systems means examining the way work is done and changing organizations themselves. Thus, the question naturally arises as to what basic action and process approaches designers can use to conceptualize and analyze human activity and change. The design of socially embedded systems also has to do with representations in several ways. Representations serve as part of systems themselves (e.g., as representations of knowledge or of processes), and they also serve as tools and methods in design processes. All of the chapters in the Ibis section have something to say about the nature and practice of representation, and about its critical role in system content and in the design process. The treatment of design itself is a third dimension that connects them. Design is treated as a key phase in the process >>of integrating technical systems …\n"
